@Credib1eGuy Strongly disagree. 

With options you’re making multiple bets at once: Vega, delta, rho, gamma 

You can be right on one and be right on the thesis but still get smoked on Vega for example 

Perps are linear and a cleaner exposure to delta

Not really. Every time you transact with an options you are taking a view on its implied volatility. 

Your point about selling covered calls: yes on the surface it’s simple and can be explained easily however explain that the IV you sell that call at can make or break the profitability of the trade is not simple. 

Considering the vast majority of people that buy options lose money, I really don’t think I’m over complicating it

I get that you work for an options platform and are incentivized to promote it as being simple, but I would push back and say that forecasting volatility is incredible complex and goes under discussed and since it’s baked into the price of the option you pay for it matters every single time even if you’re trading delta

@FlowTraderTM @muir_eth @Credib1eGuy “You could explain covered calls and cash secured puts to a 5 year old” https://t.co/c1PLf8XTMf

@muir_eth @Credib1eGuy i cant think of any sort of options trade that doesn't depend on IV and having a view on it other than if you were buying deep ITM 100 delta options

I would say that being right on the delta positioning but being wrong on IV is an equally frustrating experience. There are many people that bought puts when gamestop crashed that still lost money because IV also crashed.

I guess my main point here is that people should use different derivatives for different strategies.

